5|$|The Tagora was priced {{to overlap}} with {{high-end}} Peugeot 505 and low-end Citroën CX models, while slotting in beneath the Peugeot 604. Its pricing was also {{comparable to the}} Renault 20/30 and Ford Granada. The Tagora was in the 20,000–30,000 <b>Deutschmark</b> bracket in Germany. During the first fifteen months of the car's existence, in 1980/81, a mere 16,169 Tagoras were produced which was only one quarter of Chrysler's initial projections. Sales proved insufficient even for this production level, and volumes plummeted by more than 80 percent in 1982. In 1983 the sales figures prompted PSA to cancel the model altogether. By the time the Tagora was discontinued, only about 20,000 had been built; by comparison, over 116,000 Peugeot 505s and 74,000 Citroën CXs were made in 1981 alone.|$|E
