5000|$|At {{the same}} time, the government, {{following}} Erhard's advice, cut taxes sharply on moderate incomes. Walter Heller, a young {{economist with the}} U.S. occupation forces who was later to become chairman of President Kennedy's Council of Economic Advisers, wrote in 1949 that to [...] "remove the repressive effect of extremely high rates, Military Government Law No. 64 cut a wide swath across the German tax system {{at the time of}} the currency reform." [...] Individual income tax rates, in particular, fell dramatically. Previously the tax rate on any income over 6,000 <b>Deutschmark</b> had been 95 percent. After tax reform, this 95 percent rate applied only to annual incomes above 250,000 <b>Deutschmark.</b> For the West German with an annual income of about 2,400 <b>Deutschmark</b> in 1950, the marginal tax rate fell from 85 percent to 18 percent.|$|E
